This challenge is how can I enforce additional restrictions on a foreign key by default, based on known filters in a queryset manager on a model.

For example, a database has posts some which aren't published and aren't visible.

```
class ArticleQuerySet(models.QuerySet):
    def visible(self, user):
        if user.is_superuser:
            return self
        return self.filter(publish=True)

class Article(models.Model):
    objects = ArticleManager()
    title = fields.TextField()
    is_published = fields.BooleanField()

class Comment(models.Model):
    article = fields.ForeignKey(Article)
    comment = fields.TextField()
```

I know that I can properly resolve posts to keep these hidden:

```
class Query(graphene.AbstractType):
    all_articles = DjangoFilterConnectionField(ArticleType)
    all_comments = DjangoFilterConnectionField(CommentType)

    def all_posts (self, args, context, info):
        return Article.objects.visible(context.user)
```

But if I also want to query by comments, like so:

```
class Query(graphene.AbstractType):
    all_articles = DjangoFilterConnectionField(ArticleType)
    all_comments = DjangoFilterConnectionField(CommentType)

    def all_posts (self, args, context, info):
        return Article.objects.visible(context.user)
```

By default, I can actually see into the uncommented posts:
```
query {
  allComments {
    comment
    postSet {
      title 
      published
    }
  }
}
```

The above query allows me to access all articles, even if I'm not a superuser! So, is there some way (Django-, or Graphene-based) that allows me to prevent users from querying into objects they haven't got permission to?

Let me propose an extension:
Sometimes it would be nice if a string could be passed from a Python script to a C++ function where an `enum` parameter is expected. For example:

```c++
struct Pet {
    enum Kind {
        Dog = 0,
        Cat
    };
    Pet(Kind type) : type(type) { }
    Kind type;
};
```

Binding code:
```c++
auto pet = py::class_<Pet>(m, "Pet")
    .def(py::init<Pet::Kind>());

py::enum_<Pet::Kind>(pet, "Kind")
    .value("Dog", Pet::Kind::Dog)
    .value("Cat", Pet::Kind::Cat);
```

Python:
```python
>>> p = Pet(Pet.Cat) # Works
>>> p = Pet("Cat")   # Would like to make this work too
```

In principle it is possible to add optional support for this implicit conversion from a Python string to the enum type. I propose to add the following method to the ``pybind11::enum_`` class:

```c++
template <typename Type> class enum_ : public class_<Type> {
    ...

    /// Set up atomatic Python string -> C++ enum conversion.
    enum_& enable_conversion_from_string() {
        auto entries = m_entries;
	def("__init__", [entries](Type& v, const char* str) {
            for(const auto& item : *entries) {
                if(!strcmp(str, item.second)) {
                    v = (Type)item.first;
                    return;
                }
            }
            std::string tname = typeid(Type).name();
            detail::clean_type_id(tname);
            throw value_error("\"" + std::string(str) + "\" is not a valid value for enum type " + tname);
        });
	implicitly_convertible<str, Type>();
        return *this;
    }
    ...
}
```

This would allow writing binding codes like this:
```c++
py::enum_<Pet::Kind>(pet, "Kind")
    .value("Dog", Pet::Kind::Dog)
    .value("Cat", Pet::Kind::Cat)
    .enable_conversion_from_string();
```

There is only one problem with this solution: The exception thrown by the conversion constructor when the string does not match any of the enum entries is swallowed by pybind11. Instead, a general cast error is raised because the conversion from string to the enum type failed.

I am wondering what you think about this idea. Does it make sense to offer an automatic conversion like this? At least in my project there is one situation where an automatic conversion from a string is desirable.

By the way: The ``pybind11::enum_`` class constructor registers two ``__init__`` methods: One initializing the value via assignment, the other via in-place new. I think one of them is redundant. Furthermore, I noticed that the ``std::unordered_map`` allocated by the constructor is never freed. Does it make sense to use a ``shared_ptr<unordered_map>`` here so that the map gets destroyed eventually?

Whenever a program using Ray is killed from the command line via kill -9 <PID>, the worker threads it spawns aren't killed. This can be reproduced by executing the program below, via

python main.py

Is it possible to kill all worker threads instead?

As suggested by @robertnishihara , one gets different behaviour depending on how the program is killed. In particular, this issue doesn't arise if the main python process is killed with a KeyboardInterrupt. 

The corresponding issue with the ProcessPoolExecutor from the python standard library concurrent.futures is discussed here: 

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29177490/how-do-you-kill-futures-once-they-have-started 

```python
import ray
from time import sleep

@ray.remote
def g(x):
    sleep(100)
    return x

@ray.remote
def func2():
    x = g.remote(100)
    y = g.remote(200)
    return ray.get(x) + ray.get(y)

@ray.remote
def func1():
    x = g.remote(1)
    y = g.remote(2)
    return ray.get(x) + ray.get(y)

def main():
    ray.init()
    print "Program ended: ", ray.get([func1.remote(), func2.remote()])

if __name__ == "__main__":
    print "Program started."
    main()
```
